		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Cogendus sibi quisqu[e]: idq[ue] quotidiana necessitate:
						aut quotidi&egrave; quisq[ue] frigescet,
						pl&ugrave;s, min&ugrave;s.
						Sola coacta Sibi ipsis pra[e]stant.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				One must drive oneself; and it must be done by necessity daily,
				otherwise, daily one becomes cold, more, less.
				Only with <!-- CG: Not sure about the translation here. --> <!--JG: Perhaps: 'Everyone must drive themselves; and it must be done by
					necessity daily, othersiwe, daily everyone becomes cold, more, less. Only things compelled by themselves, are responsible for themselves.' Not sure at all though-->
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nunq[uam] hebetandus, aut obscurandus animi
						splendor: sed nitidissim&egrave; semper fouenda 
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						pars a[e]therea.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The splendor of the mind must never be dulled or obscured, but the heavenly part must always be favored most brightly.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Viuidus exultat nocte, dieq[ue] vigor.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The lively man exults vigor by day and by night.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="EN">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						The Toung, the great allectiue: the Hart, the great attractiue: the Hand, the great extensiue.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Desperatarum rerum remedium, Crocus. Meorum Emblematum Vnum.
						Crocus fortunam propri&egrave; mutat: Nec vlla Planta, aut omnin&ograve; aliud desperatis rebus
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						tam auxilium affert.
						Cardanj l. I.
						Synes. Somnio c. 30. de plantis.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Girolamo Cardano"/>
					<book title="Somniorium synesorium"/>					
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The cure for desparate matters, the crocus. One of my emblems.
				The crocus changes ones own fortune. No plant, or anything else, is able to completely bring as much help
				for desparate situations.
				Cardano Book 1.
				Somniorium synesorium, chapter 3, on plants.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Aurea etiam Aqua vita[e], mirificam habet virtutem alterantem.\
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Even the golden water of life has a wonderful further virtue.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
